				\begin{document}$$ {\mu}_c,{\mu}_{ck},{\beta}_c,{\beta}_{ck}^{(I)} $$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M34" display="inline"><mml:msub><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi><mml:mi>c</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">ck</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>β</mml:mi><mml:mi>c</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>β</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">ck</mml:mi><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:mi>I</mml:mi></mml:mfenced></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="13059_2020_2126_Article_IEq14.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> are regression coefficients to be estimated, and * denotes the interaction term and where we assume <italic>K</italic> cell types and that errors are Gaussianly distributed with a variance that may depend on the specific CpG <italic>c</italic>. The regression coefficients <inline-formula id="IEq15"><alternatives><tex-math id="M35">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
